Provides `OrderedMap` (an insertion-ordered `string -> string` map, mirroring JS object key semantics) and `to_json`, a hand-rolled serializer producing `JSON.stringify`-compatible output for exact parity with a TypeScript reference implementation — used wherever steno needs byte-identical JSON output to the TS tool it's porting/mirroring.

`to_json` emits one entry per line: `{\n"k": "v",\n...\n}\n`, empty map as `"{}\n"`, no trailing comma on the last entry, keys/values in `OrderedMap` insertion order (not sorted). String escaping matches JS `JSON.stringify`: `"`, `\`, `\n`, `\r`, `\t` get their short escapes, other control chars below `0x20` become `\u00XX` (lowercase hex), everything else — including non-ASCII — passes through unescaped (no `\uXXXX` escaping of unicode, unlike some JSON serializers).

`OrderedMap::insert` returning `Some(prev)` on overwrite keeps the key's original position in iteration order — updating a key does not move it to the end. `len`/`is_empty` reflect distinct key count via `order`, not `map` (they should stay consistent since insert always keeps both in sync). No dependency on `serde_json` or any JSON crate — deliberately zero-dependency to keep escaping behavior exactly matched to the TS source rather than to serde's conventions; if the TS tool's stringify behavior changes (e.g. different escaping rules), this file must be updated by hand, not via a library upgrade.